<h2>HVAC Systems for Louisville</h2>
<p>Louisville's Cold-Mixed climate demands versatile HVAC systems capable of handling summer temperatures reaching the mid-80s and winter lows dipping into the 20s. For optimal efficiency, homeowners should consider heat pumps with SEER ratings of 16-20 for cooling and HSPF ratings of 9-10 for heating. These systems work exceptionally well in Louisville's moderate climate, providing both heating and cooling while maintaining energy efficiency year-round.</p>

<p>Traditional split systems with gas furnaces remain popular in Louisville, particularly for larger homes exceeding 2,000 square feet. A 14-16 SEER air conditioner paired with a 90-95% AFUE gas furnace provides reliable comfort for Jefferson County's climate patterns. For maximum efficiency, consider variable-speed systems that adjust output based on demand, reducing energy consumption during Louisville's mild spring and fall seasons when full heating or cooling isn't necessary.</p>

<p>Ductless mini-split systems are gaining popularity in Louisville's historic neighborhoods where ductwork installation is challenging. These systems offer SEER ratings up to 30 and provide zone-by-zone climate control, perfect for the varied room sizes found in Louisville's diverse housing stock. The investment typically ranges from \$3,000-\$8,000 depending on the number of zones needed.</p>

<h2>Louisville Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Louisville residents can take advantage of the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit on solar installations through 2032. This credit applies to the entire system cost, including equipment, installation, and permits. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, homeowners receive a \$6,000 federal tax credit, significantly reducing the overall investment.</p>

<p>Kentucky offers additional incentives through the Kentucky Power Solar Share program and various utility rebates. LG&E provides rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, offering up to \$400 for ENERGY STAR certified air conditioners and up to \$600 for qualifying heat pumps. The utility also participates in the Home Energy Efficiency Program, providing rebates for comprehensive home energy improvements that often pair well with solar installations.</p>

<p>Jefferson County occasionally offers property tax exemptions for renewable energy systems, and Louisville Metro has implemented streamlined permitting processes for solar installations. These local initiatives, combined with federal and state incentives, can reduce total system costs by 35-45%, making solar increasingly attractive for Louisville homeowners.</p>

